{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01KueXj1kaTRi6CbZz2XMMhs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything is already routing correctly, and consistently so (5/5 runs). Let me verify the deciding configuration is sound rather than coincidental.\n\nThe routing is governed by two Ingresses on `canary.example.com`:\n\n- **`canary-stable`** — the main Ingress, routes `/` → `stable-echo`.\n- **`canary-canary`** — a canary overlay with:\n  - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary: \"true\"`\n  - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary-by-header: X-Canary`\n  - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary-by-header-value: always`\n  - backend → `canary-echo`\n\nThis is exactly the correct header-based canary configuration: only requests with `X-Canary: always` divert to `canary-echo`; everything else falls through to the stable backend.\n\n## Result\n\nBoth test requests pass, repeatably:\n\n| Request | Body |\n|---|---|\n| No header | `stable` ✅ |\n| `X-Canary: always` | `canary` ✅ |\n\nThe original symptom (\"canary traffic not reaching the canary backend\") was because the `canary-echo` / `stable-echo` backends were still coming up during stage setup — the pods became `Ready` only ~20s before I tested, and the Ingress annotations themselves were already correct. With the backends now `1/1 Running`, the `canary-by-header` rule resolves correctly.\n\nNo changes to the application Deployments or Services were needed (or made). Both success criteria are met."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":441,"cache_read_input_tokens":31671,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":441},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"02178108-4b53-4f91-9a15-874d03aa39ba","uuid":"a66b3f18-0840-41a6-b9ee-07bf1